## East Germany

**East Germany**, officially the **German Democratic Republic** (GDR; in [German](/German_language): *Deutsche Demokratische Republik*, **DDR**), was a state that existed from 1949 to 1990, the period when Germany was divided into [West Germany](/West_Germany) and East Germany. It was an area of [Soviet occupation](/Soviet_Union) that was established in the Soviet zone of occupation of [Germany](/Germany) after [World War II](/World_War_II). It was a [communist state](/Communism) with its capital in [East Berlin](/East_Berlin).

The GDR was a member of the [Warsaw Pact](/Warsaw_Pact) and the [Council for Mutual Economic Assistance (Comecon)](/Council_for_Mutual_Economic_Assistance) and was considered one of the leading nations of the [Eastern Bloc](/Eastern_Bloc). It was characterized by a centrally planned economy, a one-party political system dominated by the [Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED)](/Socialist_Unity_Party_of_Germany), and the pervasive surveillance activities of the [Stasi](/Stasi), the state security service.

The official ideology of the GDR was [Marxism-Leninism](/Marxism-Leninism), and its government was established with the support of the Soviet Union. The country’s existence was marked by a struggle for international recognition, a constant drain of skilled labor to the West, and the construction of the [Berlin Wall](/Berlin_Wall) in 1961 to prevent emigration. Despite its ideological isolation and internal repression, the GDR achieved notable successes in areas such as education, healthcare, and sports, particularly in [Olympic Games](/Olympic_Games).

The GDR ceased to exist as a separate entity on October 3, 1990, when it was reunified with the Federal Republic of Germany (West Germany) as part of the [German reunification](/German_reunification) process. The transition to a market economy and democratic system proved challenging, and the legacy of the GDR continues to be debated and analyzed.

